docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — It’s hard to imagine how smartphones could get much better. Most are already zippy and equipped with jumbo screens, powerful cameras and face scanners.

headline.main: What’s Next for Smartphones? Samsung’s New Galaxy Line Offers a Few Answers
headline.print_headline: A Glimpse of What’s Next for Smartphones

docs.abstract: Old Navy will become its own public company, while Gap will form another public company made up of its namesake label and its other brands like Banana Republic.
docs.snippet: Old Navy will become its own public company, while Gap will form another public company made up of its namesake label and its other brands like Banana Republic.
docs.lead_paragraph: Gap, one of the largest operators of mall stores in the United States, said on Thursday that it planned to spin off Old Navy into a separate public company, drawing a line between the family-friendly apparel chain and its classic, more expensive brands.

headline.main: Gap Plans to Spin Off Old Navy After a Dismal Year
headline.print_headline: Gap Plans  A Spinoff  To Unmoor Old Navy

docs.abstract: Chrysler, Ford and General Motors saw a booming Chinese driving culture and cheap labor. Now the market is slowing, competition is rising and the Trump administration wants limits.
docs.snippet: Chrysler, Ford and General Motors saw a booming Chinese driving culture and cheap labor. Now the market is slowing, competition is rising and the Trump administration wants limits.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHONGQING, China — For Detroit, China once meant opportunity. The country’s growing ranks of drivers bought cars by the millions. Its cheap labor gave American automakers dreams of someday exporting their Chinese-made cars to the United States. The Big Three bet billions of dollars there.

headline.main: China Shifts, and Detroit’s Big Bet Goes Sour
headline.print_headline: Detroit’s Bet on China Is Looking Iffy

docs.abstract: A surprise ruling accuses several Fox executives of a “pattern of deceit” in how they divvied up the profits for a crime show that lasted 12 seasons.
docs.snippet: A surprise ruling accuses several Fox executives of a “pattern of deceit” in how they divvied up the profits for a crime show that lasted 12 seasons.
docs.lead_paragraph: A private arbitrator ruled this month that Fox must pay the extraordinary sum of $178.7 million to former producers and stars of the procedural crime television series “Bones” in a dispute over profit participation.

headline.main: Arbitrator Scolds Fox and Orders It to Pay $178 Million to ‘Bones’ Team
headline.print_headline: Fox Stunned by Penalty Over ‘Pattern of Deceit’

docs.abstract: The online retailer said it would consider parting with the ticket-sales service and its classifieds business as part of a settlement with Elliott Management and Starboard Value.
docs.snippet: The online retailer said it would consider parting with the ticket-sales service and its classifieds business as part of a settlement with Elliott Management and Starboard Value.
docs.lead_paragraph: EBay said on Friday that it would consider selling the ticket-sales service StubHub, its classified advertising unit and other assets in a potential revamping of the online retailer meant to appease restive shareholders.

headline.main: EBay to Consider Selling StubHub in Peace Deal With Activist Hedge Funds

docs.abstract: Departing from the industry’s longtime opposition, the automaker endorsed a mandate for vehicles to have alerts and precautions to address the hazard.
docs.snippet: Departing from the industry’s longtime opposition, the automaker endorsed a mandate for vehicles to have alerts and precautions to address the hazard.
docs.lead_paragraph: Forgetting to shut off a keyless vehicle has been a safety hazard for years, causing a growing number of carbon-monoxide deaths. But a proposed regulation to require warning signals and other precautions has languished in the face of opposition from the auto industry.

headline.main: G.M. Backs Rule to Curb Carbon-Monoxide Risk in Keyless Cars
headline.print_headline: G.M. Backs Rule to Curb Keyless Risks

docs.abstract: Robert Lighthizer, the president’s top trade adviser, sounded a more cautious note than his boss when talking about the potential for a trade deal with China.
docs.snippet: Robert Lighthizer, the president’s top trade adviser, sounded a more cautious note than his boss when talking about the potential for a trade deal with China.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Robert Lighthizer, the president’s top trade adviser, cautioned lawmakers on Wednesday that hurdles remain to reaching a significant trade deal with China but said the administration’s talks represent the best hope for resetting economic terms between the two nations.

headline.main: Trump Trade Adviser Defends China Deal Before Congressional Skeptics
headline.print_headline: Trade Chief Defends ‘Not Perfect’ China Deal

docs.abstract: The Trump administration accuses Beijing of forcing foreign companies to hand over technological secrets. A new law in the works tries to address such concerns.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration accuses Beijing of forcing foreign companies to hand over technological secrets. A new law in the works tries to address such concerns.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — China is poised to approve a sweeping rewrite of the country’s laws on foreign investment that it hopes will help pacify the United States and ease a rancorous trade dispute. The new rules would respond to some concerns among foreign governments and businesses but disregard many other worries.

headline.main: China Law Responds to U.S. Investment Demands. Critics Say It’s Not Enough.
headline.print_headline: Plans to Open Up China Investment Disappoint Critics
